Civil Rights Movement issues travel alert for Missouri
The National Association for the Advancement of Colored People (NAACP) has issued a warning to people of color traveling to Missouri on the basis of discriminatory state policies and racist attacks.
The NAACP Travel Recommendation for the State of Missouri, effective August 28, 2017, calls on African-American travelers, visitors, and residents of Missouri to pay increased attention when traveling across the state as a result of a series of contentious racially motivated incidents currently occurring throughout the state.
The NAACP said the move was based on Missouri’s current laws, which make it difficult to defend racist-motivated acts in court, as well as the actions of law enforcement agencies that disproportionately target minorities.
“Civil rights are being violated.
People are stopped by police just because of the color of their skin, attacked or killed,” Rod Chapel, president of the NAACP, told the Kansas City Star.
"We have the largest number of complaints to date."
This is the first warning of its kind issued by the organization for the U.S. state.
Among the incidents cited by the organization were racially motivated abuse directed at black students at the University of Missouri and the death of Tory Sanders, a black man from Tennessee.
Sanders died in contentious circumstances earlier this year after running out of gas while traveling across the state and was thrown into custody by police without charge of a crime.
The travel recommendation also draws attention to a recent statement by the Missouri Attorney General’s Office that black drivers are 75% more likely to be stopped by police.
“The purpose of the travel recommendation is to alert people and warn their families, friends and co-workers about what could happen in Missouri,” Chapel said.
"People need to be prepared - they should bring money with them for a possible bail payment or alert their relatives that they are going to travel across the state."
According to the FBI’s current hate crime reporting program, there were 100 hate crimes reported in Missouri in 2015, putting the state in 16th place among all states.
The travel alert is also a response to the new Missouri law, which makes it difficult to sue a company for discrimination in providing accommodation or employment.
The American Civil Liberties Union (ACLU) has issued travel recommendations for Texas and Arizona after states passed an immigration law that allows state officials to detain people for violating the law, which the ACLU says aims to improve racial profiling.
Travel recommendations are usually issued by the Foreign Office, but recently advocacy groups have resorted to these measures in response to specific laws and trends within the U.S.
