Poverty and Death in Indonesia’s Gold Country
When Bardina Degei cooks dinner, she does not use the stove.
In fact, he rarely uses a frying pan.
In her wooden hut, located in the capital Paniai Enarotali in the Indonesian province of Papua, a woman usually simply throws a sweet potato - in the local language "note" - directly into the fire.
After half an hour, remove the potato and taste it with unwashed hands.
Bardina sits on muddy ground - the house is not equipped with furniture - where he also does his daily work, such as washing clothes in the muddy water from the nearby swamp.
A bucket in a room without a roof supplants the toilet.
As the youngest of her husband's four wives, she was not assigned any field to cultivate.
Polygamy is common here.
Working late into the night poses a danger: most of the men in the village are unemployed and often drink alcohol, and the village is also home to soldiers.
"In the afternoon, after five o'clock, no one dares to wander around the village," Bardina says.
It is a rare glimpse into everyday life in the highlands of Papua, a former Dutch colony that was declared part of Indonesia in 1969 after a controversial referendum in which only 1,026 elders were forced to vote by public show of hands before the occupying army.
The current anti-Dutch protest movement quickly turned its anger against the Jakarta government, which controlled the entire region with the exception of foreign journalists or civil rights monitors.
In 2003, the province was officially divided into Papua and West Papua - an independent Papua New Guinea occupied the eastern part of the island.
Enarotali is such a remote and desolate city, where you can reach after a ninety-minute flight from the capital of the province of Jayapura to Nabire, and then a five-hour stomach-hugging ride.
Public transport does not work at this location.
The city of 19,000 inhabitants consists of wooden houses surrounded by bamboo fences, roofs made of woolen sheets in shades of gray and rusty.
Very few Indonesians, let alone journalists, and practically no foreigners, looked at this place.
Before the arrival of Christians, the locals worshipped a god named Uga Tamee.
And that's not all.
“We weren’t used to wearing this dress,” says Bardina, pointing to his colorful, hand-knitted turban, dark T-shirt and radiant skirt.
"We used to only carry leaves."
Papua is the poorest province in Indonesia, with 28% of the population living below the poverty line, and child mortality and literacy rates are among the worst in all of Asia.
It is also the gold of Indonesia.
The world’s largest and most profitable gold mine, Grasberg, owned by Freeport McMoran of Phoenix, is located just 60 miles from Paniai, a rocky province roughly the size of New Jersey that is home to about 153,000 residents.
In 2015 alone, Freeport mined $3.1 billion worth of gold and copper.
In addition, Papua supports an estimated $78 billion worth of logging.
However, these riches are a source of suffering for the Papuans and a guarantee of oppression by the powerful Indonesian army.
According to a 2005 New York Times investigation, Freeport paid about $20 million to local military officials and units between 1998 and 2004, including $150,000 per officer.
Papuans calling for self-government threaten this golden goose and are therefore severely repressed.
According to human rights activists, more than 500,000 Papuans have been killed since 1969, and thousands more have been raped, tortured and imprisoned by the Indonesian military.
Mass killings in the Papuan tribal region during the 1970s amounted to genocide, according to the Asian Commission on Human Rights.
Last year alone, Indonesian police arrested more than 3,900 peaceful protesters in the region.
We Will Lose Everything, a 2016 report by the Archdiocese of Brisbane, describes the atrocities that took place last year as extrajudicial executions, torture – according to another report, rape and electrocution are particularly popular – and the brutal repression of peaceful protesters.
“It’s difficult to count the number of victims because incidents happen every week,” said Andreas Harsono, an Indonesian researcher at Human Rights Watch.
The situation was aggravated by the fact that Papuan resources were attracting colonists to Indonesia.
Of the province's 3.5 million inhabitants, 83% profess Christianity, but the demographics are changing with the influx of Muslim immigrants from the Indonesian islands of Java, Borneo, Sumatra and Sulawesi.
Javan canteens sell fried chicken and gado-gado, or a mixture of vegetables with peanut sauce.
Local people are struggling to survive.
“Immigrants started selling chicken and vegetables in traditional markets at lower prices than local Papuans,” explains 24-year-old Abeth You, who was born in Paniai and moved to work in the provincial capital of Jayapura.
"The original inhabitants of Papua - mom-mom (women) - lost their jobs."
Indonesian President Joko Widodo, nicknamed Jokowi, promised to tackle inequality and rights violations as part of his 2014 presidential campaign.
The former carpenter also secured his way to the presidential palace in Jakarta, 27 of the 29 districts of Papua, including Paniai.
But very little has changed in Papua, and the local people feel betrayed.
“Our hearts were broken because in 2014 we voted for Jokpwi in the hope that he would hear our call for justice,” You said.
The fact is that just two months after Jakowi's October inauguration, Paniai experienced a great shock.
On December 7, 2014, a group of 11 children were singing Christmas carols at a camp fire in the town of Enarotali when two Indonesian soldiers on motorbikes emerged from the gloom of the night.
Two of the surprised children told them to turn on the lights.
One of the soldiers was touched by this reproach and the tone with which it was uttered, and later returned with four other soldiers, said the local priest Yavedt Tebai.
Two of the soldiers in a drunken state chased a group of children and beat them with the butts of their weapons, victims and witnesses of the event said.
One of the soldiers then fired on a group of children.
One of the children, 16-year-old Yulianus Yeimo, was beaten so hard that he fell into a coma.
A few hours later, someone set fire to a nearby election commission building, and the next day things escalated.
About 1,000 young Papuan men and women gathered on a football pitch outside the local police station and army headquarters to demand justice.
They came with ceremonial hunting bows and performed a waita dance - in which one runs in a circle and imitates the singing of birds - of the Papuan tribe Mee Pago.
Several Protestants began to throw stones at the buildings.
With increasing tension, the soldiers were ordered over the radio: “If the crowd tries to resist at least three times, you are allowed to shoot,” according to an official document, the contents of which were never published in the local media.
Yeremias Kayame, 56, the head of Enarotali district, Kego Koto, recognized the danger and urged residents to disperse to their homes.
But no one paid attention to his words.
"When I turned around, someone shot me in the left wrist," he told TIME magazine on the porch of his colorfully painted wooden house.
Kayame does not yet know who the shooter was, but he said the bullet belonged to one of the soldiers present.
"There were a lot of people around and a lot of shooting," he added.
One of the locals, Alfius Youw, said his cousin, who witnessed the shooting, had been hit three times.
“I ran to the body to make sure it was really him,” Yohanes, who like many Indonesians uses only one name, told TIME in a sullen voice.
"I saw he was dead... I kissed him."
The Papuan police inspector, General Yotje Mende, told reporters that his officers were only “securing” the station under attack.
“We have to defend ourselves when people threaten us with death,” a spokesman for the Papuan police, Commissioner Pudjo Sulistiyo, said in 2015.
"It's a matter of life and death."
According to Human Rights Watch, five protesters were killed and many escaped injuries.
The news of the killings made headlines in the Jakarta media the following day.
Three weeks later, Jokowi gave a passionate speech in Jayapur, expressing his understanding for the families of the victims and promising to address the violence in Papua.
"I demand an immediate solution to this problem so that it can never be repeated," he said.
National Security Minister Wiranto announced in October 2016 that he would introduce an out-of-court mechanism to resolve acts of violence that have occurred in the past.
Almost immediately, however, the excuses began to come.
“Most of the violent acts took place a long time ago.
Some of them occurred in the 90s of the last century and some at the beginning of the 21st century.
I mean, we are determined to punish these violent acts, but it will not be an easy task,” he said.
However, in a June 5 interview with TIME, held in Jakarta, Wiranto claimed that he did not plan to introduce any measures in Papua.
Instead, he said, “all cases will be brought to court.”
Wiranto, who was indicted by the UN for “crimes against humanity” on the basis of more than 1,000 deaths during the 1999 independent elections in East Timor, said 11 cases of human rights violations in Papua, including the Paniai incident, had been settled so far.
The families of the victims of the shooting in Paniai welcomed his claims with distrust.
“I’ve been interviewed four times in the last three years, but so far I haven’t seen anything,” Yohanes said.
"I'm tired."
A few years later, he says, he still lives in fear.
"I'm afraid," he says.
"I'm afraid I'll be arrested by the army or shot."
His brother Yacobus confirmed the view of many Paniai residents who are afraid to speak out about the incident.
According to him, he was beaten by members of the army after helping to bury four of the victims.
"After the bodies were buried, the army started looking for me," he said.
And the shooting hasn't stopped yet.
On Tuesday, Indonesian police shot at villagers in neighboring Deiyai.
The skirmish, in which one person died and another 17 were injured, took place between villagers and a construction company manager who refused to provide assistance in transporting an unconscious man to hospital.
Ravianus Douw, 24, who drowned while fishing in a nearby river, died on his way to hospital.
Angry villagers protested in front of the company building.
According to the police, the villagers threw stones at the members and the response was a warning shot.
Locals say the mobile brigade (Indonesian paramilitary police) started shooting at the crowd and killed one person.
“There was a panic, we were afraid of retribution,” Domingo Badii, 29, who lives near the hospital and witnessed the arrival of the injured, told TIME.
"I didn't leave the house for two days."
The Deiyai parliament demanded the punishment of the participating police officers and the withdrawal of the mobile brigade from the area.
Paniai has always been a thorn in the side of the Indonesian government.
The lack of meaningful development only deepens the separation of the Mee, Moni, Dani and Damal tribes living in the central highlands.
Many of them have joined the Papua Liberation Movement (OPM), an army of rebels that protects the rights of Papuans by attacking and kidnapping Indonesian police officers.
Some of the OPM leaders come from Paniai, including Tadius Yogi and Daniel Yudas Kogoya.
As a result of the attacks, the army has arrested and arbitrarily detained thousands of Paniai residents in recent years, all under the pretext of “ensuring national sovereignty.”
Some of them will never be seen again.
Paniai is known as a “tragic and forgotten place” among the people of Papua.
The fuel for the fire is poverty.
The little rice that is sold in Enarotali is too expensive for the locals.
The bread is unreachable.
The locals grow their own food: mainly sweet potatoes, fruits and leafy vegetables.
Women work in the fields; each of them cultivates four or five fields of sweet potatoes.
Most of the harvest is intended for the needs of the family, the rest are sold in the local market.
Ten pieces of sweet potatoes cost only 10,000 Indonesian rupees (75 cents).
Since the airport opened more air routes and new immigrants began to flow into the country, there has been an increase in economic inequality between native Papuans and immigrants.
Fewer jobs are usually filled by more educated and wealthy immigrants.
Papuans rarely have the capital and education they need to start a business.
“Young people are moving out of villages because of a lack of jobs and money,” said John Gobai, chairman of the Paniai tribal council.
Thanks to the isolation, the province of Papua is hidden from the world.
Strict rules for foreign journalists also contribute to this.
Earlier this year, two French journalists, Franck Escudie and Basile Longchamp, were expelled from the papaya for “lack of cooperation with the authorities,” despite the fact that they were given such a rare film permit.
Phelim Kine, deputy director of the Asian branch of Human Rights Watch, promised Jokowi in his election campaign to abolish strict rules for journalists and achieve transparency and development.
“Foreign journalists working in the rebel-held easternmost regions of Papua and West Papua are at great risk: non-recognition of visas and blacklisting,” he said in a statement.
The lack of news from foreign journalists means that international pressure on the Indonesian in the case of Papua is largely limited.
In March, six Pacific nations - Tonga, Nauru, Palau, Tuvalu, Marshall Islands and Solomon Islands - urged the UN Human Rights Council to investigate "various and widespread acts of violence" in Papua, including the Paniai shooting.
These countries have also supported OPM in the past.
Indonesian Foreign Ministry spokesman Arrmanatha Nasir shrugged off the accusation when he told reporters in Jakarta that "Indonesia still has a democratic system and the media is free, so it is difficult to mask evidence of human rights violations."
Local people are calling for the participation of foreign governments.
When an official delegation from the Netherlands, led by human rights envoy Kees Van Baar, visited Jayapura on May 4, local people were chanting, according to a source who also attended the meeting but wanted to remain anonymous, the slogan “we want freedom.”
Indonesia is scheduled to hold another election in 2019, but Papuans say they will not vote for Jokowi.
"Jokowi is a man with good intentions, but he is surrounded by people associated with the shooting in Paniai," said Gobau, chairman of the tribal council.
He wants Jokowi to know that the people of Paniai — in addition to living in constant fear of a rogue army — are wallowing in poverty, poor education, and a health system.
Gobai claims that the inhabitants of Paniai, like other Papuans, consider their vote to be a “debt” that has to be repaid to Yokowi.
"They don't want money, they want justice," he added.
Despite the threats and intimidation of the families of the victims of the Paniai shootings, they continue in the last symbolic act of defiance: burying the bodies of the victims on the property opposite the police and army station.
Aware that justice will never be done enough, at least it will not allow those responsible to forget their crimes.
"A member of our family was killed," Yacobus said, his head down.
"What can we do?"
