EPA Chief Scott Pruitt on Postponement of Planned Directives to Reduce Obama Administration Emissions
After the Environmental Protection Agency was sued by fifteen states, its chief Scott Pruitt reversed his earlier decision to delay the implementation of the former Obama administration’s carbon-dioxide-reduction plan.
Pruitt has introduced changes to his plan, making it more responsive than previous governments to the needs of state environmental regulators.
However, he did not mention the legal challenge filed against his previous position in the federal appeals court.
This concerns the latest deadline set for October 1, when states should start implementing the 2015 regulation to reduce the amount of ground-level ozone.
Pruitt announced in June that he would delay the deal by one year and order a more detailed study of the plan to avoid “interference with local decisions or threatening economic growth.”
Pruitt, who served as Oklahoma’s state attorney general before being named EPA chief by President Donald Trump, has long served as a staunch opponent of tougher environmental regulations.
Since settling in Washington, Pruitt has repeatedly moved or delayed regulations proposed by the chemical and fossil industries.
Wednesday’s sudden turnaround is the biggest legal setback for Pruitt’s regulatory agenda.
Last month, a federal appeals court in Washington ruled that the EPA’s executor had exceeded his authority in an effort to delay the Obama administration’s incorporation of the plan, which required oil and gas companies to reduce methane leaks.
In a statement issued on Wednesday evening, Pruitt proposed his version of ozone standards and strengthened the EPA’s commitment to working with states through comprehensive processes and meeting new standards within a given time frame.
“During the previous administration, the EPA often missed deadlines and waited to be sued by activist groups and others, agreeing to settle and further set plans,” said Pruitt, who filed more than a dozen lawsuits against the EPA in his previous position.
“We do not believe in regulation through litigation and we take compliance with the deadline seriously.
We never joke about our status and the authority that comes with it.”
However, the EPA said in a statement that Pruitt could use “the possibility of a delay and any other legally available authority” at some point to ensure that the regulations “will be based on sound policy and the most available information.”
Republicans in Congress are pushing for a more comprehensive rewriting of the ozone rules.
The White House budget approved last month seeks to delay implementation of the 2015 rules by at least eight years.
The measure has not yet passed the Senate.
New York Attorney General Eric Schneiderman, who led a coalition of states that sued the EPA this week, said the group did not intend to allow legal pressure.
“The reversal of the EPA’s view – following our litigation – is an important victory for the health and safety of the 6.7 million New Yorkers and more than 115 million Americans who are directly affected by air pollution,” Schneiderman said.
New York was joined by California, Connecticut, Delaware, Illinois, Iowa, Maine, Massachusetts, Minnesota, New Mexico, Oregon, Pennsylvania, Rhode Island, Vermont, Washington and Washington, D.C.
Ground-level ozone occurs when common pollutants emitted by automobiles, power plants, oil refineries, chemical power plants, and other sources react in the atmosphere with sunlight.
The resulting smog can cause severe respiratory problems in sensitive people and thousands of premature deaths each year.
Public health advocates and environmentalists applaud Pruitt’s sudden change.
“It’s worrying how much pressure needs to be exerted to change the thinking of those in charge and protect the air we breathe,” said Lori Ann Burd of the Center for Biological Diversity.
“We must continue to grapple with the Trump administration’s ideological drive to help polluters and special interests.”
