China is short of tourists.
Beijing is losing billions on visa policy.
China has been trying for decades to assert its influence without the use of force.
It spends $10 billion a year to support language schools and build universities abroad, pushing its entertainment industry to foreign markets and trying to attract Western tourists.
This is not the case in Beijing.
Local state media are talking about a plan to make tourism the driving force of economic transformation and modernization.
Last year, however, the number of arrivals increased by only 3.8 percent, and about 80 percent of tourists to China came from Hong Kong, Macau and Taiwan.
This is due, among other things, to the fact that, despite all its global aspirations, China does not welcome foreigners with open arms, according to Professor of Economics at Beijing University Christopher Balding in an article for Bloomberg.
An example that speaks for itself is China’s visa policy.
Only 13 countries have visa-free travel to China, and the citizens of the others have to deal with the visa in advance.
Chinese authorities in the U.S. are, therefore, crowds comparable to the celebration of the Chinese New Year.
A visa costs $140, but if you don’t want to wait long hours in line, you have to pay $100 or more for additional services.
Such restrictions create significant economic barriers.
A study in the Journal of Economics and Finance found that the need for a visa reduced the number of visitors to a country by 70 percent.
In 2015, just two million Americans visited mainland China, while 1.8 million Americans visited Hong Kong, which accounts for less than 3 percent of China’s gross domestic product and is home to less than 1 percent of its population.
China often exacerbates this problem when it uses tourism to pursue its political goals, for example in disputes with Taiwan and South Korea.
When China cut traffic to South Korea in the spring as part of a rift over South Korea’s missile defense system, the South Koreans retaliated and avoided China.
In May, the number of visits fell by 42 percent year-on-year, while Japan saw an increase of 85 percent.
All of this has an impact on macroeconomic stability.
According to a recent report by the US Federal Reserve Bank, China could leave as much as $190 billion as a result of Chinese foreign travel, while China will receive about $35 billion a year in foreign currency sales to incoming tourists.
According to official balance-of-payments figures, China ran a $217 billion tourism deficit last year, equivalent to 44 percent of China’s total merchandise trade surplus.
Thus, a small number of tourists are inflicting a very painful blow on a country that is anxiously preventing the outflow of capital.
However, the above factors are only one manifestation of more general restraint towards foreigners.
In many parts of China, virtually no one has heard of immigrants.
In 2013, there were less than one million foreigners living in China.
There are many more cities in the United States.
Even Japan, which is not exactly a crossroads of immigration, has twice as much.
A number of scientific works show that immigrants usually revive economic growth, entrepreneurship and innovation.
You won’t find them in China.
It will be politically challenging to solve these problems, but the proposed step is to simplify the visa system.
Other Asian countries, notably India and Vietnam, have recently made great efforts to simplify and reduce the cost of visa procedures.
If China wants more foreign tourists and their hard currencies, it should be easier for them to get there.
