Moore’s Ford Bridge Massacre: Activists Recall Racist Lynching
A 1948 Ford Mercury drove past the sighting residents of Monroe, Georgia, and curled toward the Moore's Ford Bridge.
But before a car with four black passengers and a white driver could reach the bridge, a group of white men with guns blocked its way.
The leader of the group - a middle-aged man in a striped suit - pulled a cigarette for a long time and stared at the windshield of the car.
Inside, the passengers trembled with fear.
'We want that n---and Roger! 'shouted the man.
"Bring it to me!"
The silence is broken by the roar of a young black man who is pulled out of the passenger seat.
Fortunately, this scene is just a reconstruction of the events that took place on July 22.
But when one of the men throws a noose over "Roger's" neck, the audience sighs with excitement.
Since 2005, a group of activists have regularly returned to the Moore's Ford Bridge to reconstruct that fateful night in 1946 when two black couples - Roger and Dorothy Malcolm and George and Mae Murra Dorsey - were killed by members of the Kuklux Klan.
No one has ever been tried for murder.
“It’s amazing that not a single person has been arrested in all these years – even though we still see them in our community; even though we know their identity,” said Tyrone Brooks, who helped organise the reenactment.
"It's a stain on our history and a burden on our souls."
Brooks is a 71-year-old former Georgia congressman and lifelong civil rights activist.
In his eyes, the reconstruction of the event represents a dramatic call to action, reminding the Monroe community every year that justice has not been done enough.
“We demand prosecution and closure of the case, we want peace of mind and reconciliation, but above all justice,” Brooks said.
"Until then, the process of healing and reconciliation cannot begin."
On July 27, 1946, a forensic doctor covers up one of the lynching victims at Moore's Ford.
According to FBI files obtained by NBC News, up to 50 men from Monroe and surrounding counties were scheduled to participate in the lynching.
However, no one has yet been prosecuted.
Despite the suspects remaining at large for decades, civil rights advocates argue that both the reasons for the lynching – politics and sex – were known to all residents of the city.
In April 1946, by a Supreme Court decision, residents of the black state of Georgia were granted the right to participate in the elections that were scheduled for the summer for the first time.
And it was during the summer election season, according to the FBI, that black-skinned farmer Roger Malcolm was supposed to stab white-skinned landowners Barnett Hester during a skirmish - allegedly because of his wife.
According to Brooks, Hester was said to have had intercourse with Malcolm's wife Dorothy and to have brought her into a different state.
According to the FBI, on July 25, 1946, the then prominent owner of white-skinned land, Loy Harrison, made a $600 bail for Malcolm.
He was accompanied to prison by Dorothy and cousins Mae Murray and George Dorsey.
On their way back from the prison, just before the entrance to Moore's Ford Bridge, a group of suspects blocked their way.
"As it turns out, the murders were planned and orchestrated by Harrison," she said.
“It is also clear that there was a collusion between state and local law enforcement, who not only participated in the lynching, but also disposed of the evidence and concealed the identity of the witnesses.”
Brooks made a brief comment on the matter.
"It was a massacre for the right to vote," he said.
“The murders had a clear subtext for all black locals: ‘This is how you’re going to end up if you register and go to vote’.”
The annual Moore’s Ford Bridge reenactment has been organized by Cassandra Greene for almost a decade.
Her performance is pictorial, engaging and apt, showing a deep-seated racism that many would like to see extinct in modern America.
It’s not easy to watch this reconstruction, and it’s even harder to look away, but Greene says it makes sense.
“No one wants to talk about lynching, because we have to face the unpleasant feelings that lurk in each of us,” Greene said.
"But we can't have a relationship if you don't listen to what I've been through."
The main rehearsals for this year's reenactment began in June, and on the very first day, approximately 30 actors - a dozen whites, the rest blacks - rushed into the room where Greene introduced them to a very carefully planned performance.
Wade Marbaugh is an assistant director.
For many years he played the leader of the Kukluxklan, but according to him, the role is exhausting.
"It makes me feel bad because it contradicts who I am," Marbaugh said.
“I think it’s very important to remember this part of history regularly because we never want to go back to that time.”
Actors Darrius Bradshaw and Nick Rascona, who play the role of Roger Malcolm, or Barnett Hester, rehearse their roles.
The show begins with a fight - Malcolm quarrels with Hester and blames him for sleeping with his wife.
"Get off my property, n---e!"
You can't have Rascona.
There's a skirmish.
At that point, everyone (at least every black actor) will burst out laughing.
Greene laughs the most.
"What happened?" asks Rascona.
He's confused.
Was I too rude?
"No," Greene says cheerfully.
"I just don't think white people used to say 'n--r' in that tone."
"Exactly," one of the black-skinned actors blurts out.
"You have to put more emphasis on R."
The energy in the room is suddenly better; hostility replaces the feeling of rapprochement.
Everyone wants the performance to be authentic, just enough to make it look like four victims of a massacre.
The actors repeat the scene.
This time, Rascona emphasizes the correct pronunciation of the word on N.
No one's laughing now.
The show ends violently and quickly.
The roar, the gunshots... and the silence.
A woman dressed in black stands over the bodies of the actors and sings Billie Holiday's mournful song "Strange Fruit".
With every word, there is sadness in the room.
Against the background of all this, about a dozen spectators wipe sweat and tears from their eyes.
In the audience there are almost the same number of blacks and whites.
A couple had arrived from Ithaca, New York, many of whom were from nearby.
Each of them tolerates the local humid climate for almost eight hours, and Brooks leads them in a crowd to the graves of Malcolm and Dorsey.
Until now, murder could be viewed from a distance, but now, standing in the same place where the lynching took place, the atmosphere is spooky.
With the last words of the song, Greene invites the crowd to attend the inspection of the bodies.
The children knelt at the victims' heads, watching the fake blood and still bodies and whispering something in their ear.
'They're not dead, 'said the little boy.
A few minutes pass, and Greene thanks the audience.
Actors clean up the rope and wipe their tears.
Bradshaw hugs Marbaugh, the man in the suit who played the leader of the Kukluxklan.
Nick Rascona hugs his two fellow actors and weeps in their arms; in the end, he is overcome by emotion.
"It's all right," whispered one of the women.
"We know the role is against you.
But you had a reason.”
Later that day, the audience sits down with the actors for dinner.
At one table, a young white couple is passionately talking about a performance with a black couple they met today.
Denise Duplinski could hardly find the words to express her feelings about today's performance.
“It’s hard to listen to those ugly words and look at those hideous acts... done by people who look like you and do it because they look like you,” she said.
“It makes me realize that lynching is still a topical issue,” she added, adding that “it’s just called a police skirmish.”
Across the room, Tyrone Brooks sits in the courtroom, enjoying dinner while talking about civil rights.
According to his own words, he has already started planning the performance for the next year.
"The reconstruction of these events is inspiring because it describes the fear we had to experience - but it is also a moment to reflect," he said.
"If we don't learn from this, who knows... it could happen again.
People who do not know and study the history of their country are condemned to repeat it.
