Latest results of tests to determine the age limit of asylum applications in Sweden
The latest results of tests of asylum seekers in Sweden, who were subjected to a new method assessing their age, show that over 80 percent of people were asked as over 18 years old, but not everyone believes their accuracy.
The Swedish Forensic Medical Agency (R<0xC3><0x83><0xC2><0xA4>ttsmedicinalverket) started the new tests at the beginning of this year.
The aim of the method is a more accurate assessment of applicants in the framework of the evaluation of asylum applications. The measure was taken after the Swedish Migration Agency (Migrationverket) was criticized for failing to determine the correct age of some refugees who lied about their age.
To date, the Swedish Migration Agency has submitted 6,880 cases for investigation and the Forensic Medical Agency has now published the results of a total of 2,481 tests carried out from mid-March to 31 July 2017.
80 percent (2002) were judged to be over 18, while in another 25 cases the Forensic Medical Agency judged the respondent to be "possibly over 18".
In another 423 cases, it was decided that the respondent was "possibly under the age of 18".
Tests are only taken if the age of the respondent is questionable.
According to Johan G<0xC3><0x83><0xC2><0xB6>ransson of the Forensic Medical Agency, the results correspond to the previous month.
"Compared to last month, the statistics are kept in a busy track and the numbers are very similar," he told The Local.
A higher number of applicants whose age has been estimated to be over 18 does not necessarily mean that asylum seekers are lying about their age.
In May, the agency published the results of 581 tests and said that in 442 cases, it found that “the person in question is 18 years of age or older.”
The newspaper Svenska Dagbladet investigated 581 published cases and found that in 243 cases the respondent stated that he would be 18 this year.
The medical method of determining the age, which includes x-rays of wisdom teeth and MRI scans of the knee joints, which are then assessed by dentists and radiologists, has also been criticized.
One of the skeptics is Claude Marcus of the Karolinska Institute, who, among other things, deals with assessing the biological maturity of people to determine the age at which a person has gone through puberty.
“I had reason to think about this issue and I don’t think these types of measurements to assess age are correct.
Assessment of biological age is, in a sense, very uncertain.
If we cannot determine the age with accuracy, we should not pretend otherwise," he told the Metro newspaper.
The forensic medical agency Agency's G<0xC3><0x83><0xC2><0xB6>ransson defended the decision, saying: "In general, the risk of misjudging a child as an adult is small.
The highest risk is the fact that the respondent is just below the age of 18, which in this case corresponds to 10 percent of all respondents.
