Just before the decision, the bank said: “MPC predicts that gross domestic product (GDP) will stagnate in the short term along with pressure on real household incomes and a burden on consumption.”
On the subject of rates, the bank said it would need to “tighten the belts of monetary policy” to calm inflation, “to a higher degree” than markets expect.
Markets are currently forecasting first growth in the third quarter of next year and further growth in 2020.
However, the bank stressed that any increase would be "slow" and "limited".
The Bank lowered its growth forecast for this year and next year, compared to 1.9% and 1.7% forecasted in May.
The forecast growth of 1.8% in 2018 remained unchanged.
