NHS prescribes controversial HIV drug to 10,000 patients
Patients will have access to ‘transformative’ HIV prevention treatment starting in September, based on the Supreme Court’s decision to fund the NHS drug.
The National Health Service (NSH) has announced that a pre-exposure prophylaxis (PrEP) pill, which is taken before sex and reduces the risk of infection in high-risk patients by up to 86 percent, will be offered through the health service to approximately 10,000 patients within a three-year trial period.
The NSH agreed to fund a trial period after an appeals court upheld a Supreme Court decision last year saying the NHS had the funds to pay for PrEP despite saying the drug should be funded by local authorities.
The decision, which was announced on Thursday, was accepted by the NHS of England through CEO Simon Stevens as a “significant intervention”, while the National Aids Trust (NAT) described the decision as a “decisive moment”.
Sexual health clinics in London, Brighton, Manchester, Liverpool and Sheffield will be among the first to start accepting patients. Other clinics will join in October and by April 2018 there will be a full implementation across England.
Pre-exposure prophylaxis (PrEP) is an HIV drug given before sex to reduce the risk of HIV disease.
Tests have shown that PrEP significantly reduces the risk of HIV transmission between at-risk patients.
The application of PrEP before sex means that there is a sufficient amount of specific drugs in the patient's body to prevent infection.
These medications can be taken every day or at least two hours before sex.
The patients tested included gay or bisexual men, transgender people, and people with HIV-positive partners who were not successfully treated.
Clinics will identify eligible participants who sign consent to participate in testing, including men, women, transgender people, and individuals with a partner whose HIV status is not yet controlled by appropriate treatment.
People living and registered with GP in the UK can also apply to their local sexual health clinic and apply for potential participation in testing.
The programme will come to taxpayers at <0xC2><0xA3>10 million and NHS England signed a contract this week to distribute medicines after winning an international public contract.
The trial period is designed to gather clinical evidence and assess the full potential of PrEP, its targeting, use and implementation on a large scale.
Simon Stevens added: “This important intervention should complement and fully address the ever-expanding and increasingly successful HIV prevention effort.
It’s another milestone in more than 30 years of trying to stop one of the greatest challenges to human health.”
Deborah Gold, executive director of the NAT (National Aids Trust), said: “We are witnessing a decisive moment in the fight against HIV.
If PrEP is administered correctly and patients are at risk, it will offer the opportunity to transform the English HIV epidemic.
Starting in September, NSH will offer patients at high risk of HIV infection a powerful new tool that is individually controlled and not subject to the need to persuade a partner, which will lead to an improvement in the quality of many lives.
We are pleased to accept this statement."
Ian Green, executive director of the Terrence Higgins Trust, said: “The number one priority must be the rapid deployment of tests across the country; we must ensure that it is available to every patient.
We now have a trial drug, PrEP, and we are well on our way to protecting more than 10,000 people at risk of HIV infection.”
Shadow Health Minister Sharon Hodgson said: “The start of the PrEP trial period is a welcome and long-awaited change after months of delays and delays by the government.
Evidence suggests how transformative this drug can be as part of our approach to preventing HIV and ending transmission of this life-threatening infection.
Subsequent tests will take us one step closer to fully understanding the benefits of PrEP.
“It is now important that we start testing as soon as possible across the country to protect people who are exposed to HIV and to end the spread of HIV in society.”
Living on a high note: mezzanine and smart design turned this small apartment on Earls Court into a spacious home
Joanne Leigh, a former banker with a passion for real estate, swapped a large house in Knightsbridge for an apartment on the Earls Cour in 2014.
Located on the first floor of the Queen Anne smart terrace, it is a showcase of modern design that makes the most of the available space.
“Previously, I lived with my ex-husband in a much larger house in Knightsbridge,” Joanne said.
“I was looking for something at a more reasonable price.
I ran into this apartment in Earls Court and it had the same ceiling height.
I immediately fell in love with him, and on the same day I nodded at him.
Since then, the apartment of 1000 square meters has undergone a complete renovation.
One-room apartment with a complicated layout - to get into the bedroom, you had to go through the kitchen - Joanne wanted to add storage space and mezzanine to take advantage of the high ceiling.
“I wanted a high ceiling, big windows and lots of light.
Those were my demands,” she said.
To this end, she employed Erfan Azadi from the design and design studio Duck & Shed based in Notting Hill and used the nearly four-meter ceiling to create a home that was not just a project, but also a place to live.
The ceiling did not reach such a height that two gaps could climb above each other - so the challenge for the architects was to create a mezzanine on which one could walk upright.
Erfan had to engage his creative thinking.
"The steel structure is quite complicated," he explained.
“We had to organize both spaces so that we could walk upright.
It wasn’t just about building a simple platform, but also bending the steel structure to make it at the right height above and below the ceiling.”
This arrangement allowed Erfan to construct two full-fledged rooms on top of each other - and at the same time add to the drama.
The mezzanine overlooks the beautiful living room of the old copper window frames in the design of Retrouvius.
Mirror furniture in gold color, silver lines and retro chandelier Serge Mouille creates a unique style.
The use of mirrors plays an important role in drama, space and lighting.
The short corridor is provided with mirrors on both sides and looks longer.
The mirror bar in the kitchen looks like a window to the next room.
At the front door there are storage areas equipped with mirrors to store cutlery and glasses.
The advantage of the living room, which gives the whole apartment the impression of a significantly larger space, is the ability to separate it from the kitchen, if it is not used.
Folding kitchens are nothing new.
What is unique about this solution, however, is the folding door.
"We had to solve the technical side," Erfan says of the reinforced veneered doors.
"The door is fitted with counterweights to make it very easy to pull away."
Thanks to the smart use of space and storage space, Joanne gained an additional 16 square meters, a second room and a better overall layout of the apartment.
"When it comes down to it, what you're selling is a living space - or a valuation of your property," Erfan said.
"A real estate agent will, when entering an apartment, calculate its price based on the living space."
In this case, it was possible to increase the living area while maintaining high-quality materials that give the space a luxurious appearance.
“The material is very important because you touch it and you form an emotional bond with the home,” Erfan said.
“You won’t love the electricity in the walls.
Yes, they are important, but they will not win your heart.”
As it turned out, high-quality design and an increase in living space can turn an ordinary apartment into an exceptional work of art.
And like Joanne, you can finally decide to stay.
