The brothers are fighting for an empire worth more than $500 million.
Now, more than four decades after the founding of the empire by their Italian family, the two brothers are vying for one of the most expensive Victorian properties worth more than $500 million.
Former Carlton Football Club director and developer Colin De Lutis resides at Toorak Manor, just three rooms away from his younger brother Paul, who has caught up with a dispute over joint property and commercial assets to the Supreme Court.
Paul wanted to leave the family business as early as 2014, but the bitter dispute is constantly being contested before the Supreme Court.
Together with his mother, Anna, the brothers own a total of 38 properties worth more than half a billion dollars. The first store was bought by the family in 1973 on Smith Street in Collingwood.
It was here that the Westco Jeans family founded the company, which grew into a chain with 160 stone shops.
In 1999, the family sold the entire company for $85 million.
The De Lutis family’s portfolio now includes offices, building land in Brunswick and Sorrento, apartments on the Gold Coast and Mt Buller, and commercial centers in the suburbs.
Paul owns about one-third of the company’s assets, while his father, Colin, who according to Paul is the “significant driving force and dominant personality” of the De Lutis family, owns less than two-thirds of the assets.
According to court records, Colin owns $316 million in real estate, while Paul manages $176 million in real estate.
For Paul, it was the distribution of assets and funds that became problematic.
“Colin’s proposal came out in my eyes strongly in his favor,” Paul wrote in a sworn affidavit before the court in 2015.
Last Friday, after several unsuccessful attempts at reconciliation, the first session of the Supreme Court was held.
