How did one activist find out the answer to the question: ‘Whose Streets?’
On August 9, 2014, Brittany Ferrell shuddered all over her body.
The day after she arrived in New York, a native of St. Louis sat on her bed in an Airbnb room and browsed Facebook posts on her phone.
She came across the contribution of a high school student.
"Police have just shot and killed an 18-year-old man whose body is still lying in the street," it said.
She was surprised that no one else had written this post for her, so she closed Facebook and opened Twitter.
<0x40>TheePharoah constantly retweeted her wall posts.
The St. Louis rapper tweeted about the death of Michael Brown, an unarmed 18-year-old man shot dead by a white-skinned police officer in Ferguson, Missouri.
He posted a photo of Brown's body lying limp on the street, where no one had taken him after four hours.
"That's crazy," Ferrell thought.
But death was nothing new to her and her community.
She put down her phone to go back to it the night she watched tweets about people gathering on Canfield Drive.
One of the men claimed to be the father of the victim and held a sign in his hand that read "Ferguson police killed my unarmed son"!
She watched the live news - one of the policemen was standing in front of a group of protesters, holding a leash and a barking dog at the other end.
In another video, another police officer, she said, held a gun in his hand with which he aimed at the crowd and shouted, “I’m going to kill you all... animals.”
"That's not normal," Ferrell said to herself.
"This is not the type of murder we are used to and can call normal.
I could feel goose bumps all over my body.
"I was angry and I was crying."
She immediately booked a return flight and traveled home the next day.
After landing at 23:00, she picked up her six-year-old daughter from her father and decided to head to Ferguson in the morning.
The story of what happened to Ferrell and the city of Ferguson over the next three years is described in a new documentary, Whose Streets?, which will be released on August 11.
It is a story of survival and protest, love and resistance, strength and resilience told from the point of view of the people living in the community, who take to the streets and demand answers.
On her way to Ferguson, Ferrell introduced a dialogue with her daughter – dressed in a floral dress and the same floral headband – about a topic they had discussed many times before – “about the experience with black people.”
"Remember when I taught you how black people had to fight for what they believed in?" he recalls.
"We're going to Ferguson right now because the police killed an 18-year-old boy, and that's not right."
"There was no way I wouldn't take her with me," Ferrell later said.
“Today’s events are a climax... that happened in the past.
She had to know it and see it with her own eyes and grow up in it.
She needed to develop not only in activism and organizing, but also to learn the difference between the different layers of black experience and what we have to do to liberate ourselves.
Although I am able to provide her with conditions in which she will not experience racism on her own, she is in no way different from another black child-woman.
I feel that if I had protected her from this experience, I would have only hurt her.”
Upon arrival in Ferguson, South Florissant Road was the first stop across the street from the police department, which became the base of activists who were waiting for the words of police officer Darren Wilson about his possible participation in the incident.
Here Ferrell and his daughter met a local businessman who was preparing food for others.
Together, they prepared food in bags and helped distribute it to Protestants.
In Ferrell's eyes, a new type of activism was slowly emerging.
“My activism turned upside down after August 9th,” Ferrell said, adding that while studying at the University of Missouri-St. Louis, she was president of Minority Student Nurses Assn. and sought to introduce health care and food to black communities.
“I had no experience with the organization.
It was natural."
A few weeks later, Ferrell met the later co-director of the documentary, Sabaah Folayan, during an evening demonstration.
Folayan said he and her cameraman Lucas Alvarado-Farrar wanted to "just document" the ongoing events.
But Ferrell thought, “Are you working on a documentary or are you trying to find a story to use?”
This type of skepticism penetrated the community through many people, often whites, who wanted to make money on pain and determination.
As Folayan explained in an interview: “We heard that the voices of people who are born and raised in Ferguson are very often overlooked, and that’s what we wanted to change.”
Folayan has already established a collaboration with co-director Damon Davis, who is a respected local artist who deals with the topic of prisoners on death row.
His participation in the project also intrigued Ferrell and, along with six other locals, who were followed by the Whose Streets? team in the years following Brown's murder.
"No one speaks for us in this document, but it is our statement," Davis said.
"It was important to me - how these people will be represented - because I will be represented the same way."
While the aim of the documentary was not to focus on Ferrell’s experiences – in an effort to show that the movement “is not about a rescue leader, but about bringing the community closer together,” Folayan said – it turned out that she was the one most open to participating in the filming.
The documentary “Whose Streets?” thus describes a very personal aspect of Ferrell’s life, such as how she fell in love with her wife.
"I felt naked," Ferrell said with a smile on her face as she thought of the first moment she saw the final version of the document.
"But I understood that in order to do this job and humanize black people, I had to open up."
Ferrell’s story also highlights the role of the eccentric black woman in the broader aspect of the Black Lives Matter movement.
Two of the three founders of the movement – who created the #BlackLivesMatter campaign on social media in response to the 2012 murder of teenager Trayvon Martin – call themselves freaks.
“Black eccentric women in leadership positions are ultimately worth preserving the movement,” Ferrell said, “because we are constantly fighting on multiple fronts.
Black eccentric women must bear the brunt of these events.”
Folayan agrees with this statement, adding that "the movement is actually supported by black women and a large number of eccentric black women."
However, she insists that "this is not just an affirmative matter" and Ferrell is not the main heroine of the documentary because of her views.
"She was the driving force and the source of energy," she said.
"that she was in the front lines is no coincidence, for life at these crossroads in the skin of a black woman is dangerous.
You can feel the energy in front of the screen.”
Meanwhile, back in Ferguson, television cameras have cleared their positions, but severe racial ties between the community and the police persist.
Ferrell is serving a two-and-a-half-year sentence for blocking a highway during demonstrations.
She described the social and political atmosphere in the area she calls home as "a mess."
Still, she hasn’t stopped trying, which she’s committed to since she hit the streets of Ferguson three years ago.
“It is our duty to fight for our freedom.
It is our duty to win.
We must love and support each other.
The only thing we can lose is our chains.”
