A Becoming Resemblance: Artist Creates Portraits Using Chelsea Manning's DNA
In the center of one of the rooms of the New York Fridman Gallery, there are several faces of different shades of skin - white, black and brown - suspended from the ceiling on the wires. Each of them seems to fall out of the eye of the previous one.
All 30 portraits were created by artist Heather Dewey-Hagborg from mouth and hair swabs sent to her by Chelsea Manning.
Manning sent her samples from Fort Leavenworth prison, where the former analyst is serving a 35-year sentence for unauthorized publication of secret cables on WikiLeaks.
The new exhibition, which began on August 2, is called A Becoming Resemblance.
It is the result of a two-year correspondence between Dewey-Hagborg, who combines her experience in technology, computer science and the arts, and Manning, a transgender and pioneering dissident whose sentence was commuted by Obama three days before she left office.
By algorithmically analyzing Manning’s DNA and using 30 portraits to illustrate what a person with this genotype would look like, Dewey-Hagborg has created a sharp, if not intellectual commentary on DNA’s malleability – as well as the many ways DNA can be interpreted – and the inherent determinism of these interpretations, as well as the inherent identity of these interpretations.
Manning, who was born Bradley Edward Manning, was convicted in 2013 on 20 charges, including violating six spying laws, computer fraud and theft.
All of her photos were taken by the prison staff, and only one low-quality black-and-white photo was leaked to the public, on which Manning, visibly alarmed, sits in the driver's seat in the platinum blonde wig she is now associated with.
In 2015, there were still positive reactions to the 2012 Dewey-Hagborg project Stranger Visions.
As part of this project, Dewey-Hagborg used various forensic objects - such as cigarette butts and chewing gum - to create an image of the possible forms of these people.
It was at this time that she received an email from Paper Magazine.
“They were going to interview Chelsea Manning in prison and they wanted to add a portrait to the article,” Dewey-Hagborg said at the opening of the new exhibition.
However, neither visiting nor photographing were allowed, so they turned to Chelsea to ask if she would be interested in a DNA portrait.
The artist and her imprisoned muse became friends over the course of two years through correspondence.
They even created a comic book called Suppressed Images, illustrated by Shoili Kanung, which presented a vision of what would happen if Chelsea were pardoned and could attend the show in person.
In fact, President Obama asked for Manning’s release a few days after the comic’s release, a welcome change after several unbearable years in a military prison in Kansas.
Interestingly enough, the show comes at a time when Donald Trump is waging war on people who seek to expose government information and transgender soldiers while trying to find new ways to use his tweets to incite resentment in areas he should be supporting.
In response to a question about this special timing, Dewey-Hagborg said that “everything happens for a reason.”
Under the artist’s statement on one of the walls of the gallery, Manning calls with her huge signature (the letter “i” in the surname is punctuated by the heart) after the end of “self-acting factionalism based on gender, race, sexuality and culture.”
On the opposite side are the sequences of its mitochondrial DNA - the centipedes of the letters C, G and A recorded in pencil.
By including 200 letters (or nucleotides, according to the artist’s sophisticated scientific dictionary), Dewey-Hagborg wanted to illustrate how surprisingly similar, at least biologically, we all are.
“I hope that people get away with it, that our genome doesn’t care about who we are, and that genetic data is subjective and anyone can interpret it in their own way,” Dewey-Hagborg said.
"DNA tells many different stories, this is 30 of them."
The last example of the exhibition, located in a separate room, is a single page from the above graphic novel.
It depicts Manning emerging in the manner of King Kong from the United States Prison Discipline Barracks with a megaphone in her hand.
“As soon as they stop you from speaking, they win,” it says.
"Never be silenced."
"It's a direct transcript from one of the letters," the Philadelphia artist said.
"When I think about it, I get goose bumps."
Manning has not yet visited the exhibition in person - as predicted in the comic - but when she does, she will be greeted in the middle of the room with her masks, her own genomic images, arranged like a crowd of Protestants.
Which was also the purpose of the exhibition, including the almost 160 cm high statue of Maning, on which her genetic haplogroups are recorded in pencil.
“In the past, they were placed on walls, but this time I wanted to make them feel like a crowd,” Dewey-Hagborg said of the portraits.
"I wanted to give the impression of a mass movement that takes the form of Chelsea and liberates her."
