Startups that will help your company not become another Uber
Amy Errett wanted to measure the satisfaction of her startup’s e-commerce employees, but she didn’t find the right survey.
The answers were often inaccurate, unhelpful, or even misleading.
And while it promised the anonymity of the survey, some employees expressed their distrust of the entire process.
“I was looking for consistency and objectivity,” said Errett, owner of San Francisco-based hair care company Madison Reed, which employs 75 people.
He asked for help from outside.
New human resources startups are constantly appearing on the market, helping companies with employee satisfaction surveys.
By creating and licensing software with the specific intention of measuring employee responsibilities, startups allow companies to conduct quick voting, target specific teams and demographic groups, offer complete employee anonymity and a hotline for filing complaints, and in some cases also allow whistleblowers to bypass superiors and contact directors directly.
“There are tools on the market like Strava and Fitbit that track your health, but where is Fitbit for your company?” said Jim Barnett, co-founder and CEO of Reedwood City-based startup Glint.
Errett said she gained more awareness of what her employees were thinking and feeling in three years.
In addition to quick surveys and team-specific voting, Glint offers a temperature map of the company and a quick overview of the groups with the highest number of complaints, as well as an overview of the managers with low ratings - which allows the user to work on the correction.
Companies are starting to realize that it is necessary to pay attention to the culture of the working environment - in case they become another Uber - which is in turmoil after a former employee posted on his blog a post describing the corporate environment and harassment of employees who dare to speak openly.
For startups like Glint, the demand for corporate culture surveys is a lucrative business opportunity.
According to Let’s Talk Payments, a website dedicated to technical and financial progress, the value of the global control, regulation and compliance industry could exceed $118.8 billion by 2020.
Denver, Colorado-based startup Convert, which helps companies prevent and detect inappropriate behavior, saw a small increase in interest and activity at the beginning of the year, just before Uber’s scandals.
Convert’s nearly 600 clients include Airbnb, Microsoft and Tesla.
Uber has also recently taken over.
Similar to Glint, Convert allows companies to send customisable “flash” surveys, collect confidential information in real time, and display temperature maps of problem areas.
It also offers an anonymous text hotline that allows employees to report inappropriate behavior.
If the Director-General is involved in the problem, complaints are sent directly to the Management Board.
“The court of public opinion has its regulators in place,” said Patrick Quinlan, founder and CEO of Convert.
If a company is convicted of mishandling its employees or unethical behavior — and if regulators don’t intervene — it could face costly consequences as a result of customer boycotts, employee exhaustion or lawsuits, Quinlan added.
The Ruby Tuesday restaurant chain, which employs over 25,000 people across 500 locations, has been using Convercent for more than a year to raise employees’ awareness of company policies and procedures and provide an easy way to contact corporate executives.
Previously, if an employee wanted to report any problem, he had to find a phone number or e-mail to the management of the company, officially file a complaint and hope for a successful solution.
It was often a daunting and unpleasant experience, said James Vitrano, Ruby Tuesday’s general counsel, according to which there was no reliable way to track employee complaints before.
Now that the company is using Convert, it is ensuring quick detection and resolution of problems that never before reached managers sitting in offices, miles away from the actual resolution of complaints – such as discrimination, harassment or unfair treatment.
“It’s close to a holistic, holistic view of employee experience,” said Vitrano, who heads the Ruby Tuesday group of risk managers.
"At the same time, we protect shareholders from litigation by employees."
Companies stopped taking ethics, values and employee participation lightly in 2002 after accounting firm Arthur Andersen collapsed after Enron’s collapse over the abuse of employees’ ethical rights, Quinlan said.
But it wasn’t until “social media lit up” that companies began to realize that in the online world, they simply couldn’t hide their skeletons in a closet.
“Before people started using technology to track ethics, they relied on faith,” Quinlan said.
Both Glint and Convert offer their software in the form of a service for which companies pay regular fees.
It is a business model and opportunity that is endorsed by the bold capital investors who have supported both startups.
As part of his February campaign, Convert raised a total of $10 million from companies such as Sapphire Ventures and Tola Capital, and eventually raised $47 million.
Glint raised $10 million from Bessemer Venture Partners in November and raised $60 million throughout the campaign.
These investments are hardly surprising given the mutual nature of companies, culture and venture capital.
A growing body of research clearly confirms that today’s employees expect more from their workplace than ever before.
And in competitive markets such as Silicon Valley, the main advantage is not high salaries and interesting projects.
Employees want to feel that they are being accepted and appreciated and that they are devoting their time to a company that strives for a positive mission.
“If people are happy in their work, they feel that their voice is heard and that their work is rewarding, they are striving for the success of the company,” said Nina McQueen, vice president of global benefits and employee benefits at LinkedIn, which uses both Convert and Glint.
Investors make money when companies succeed and companies prosper when their employees are satisfied.
And when an analytical tool appears on the market to ensure the commitment and commitment of employees to the company, it is not surprising that there are a lot of investors who will support this effort.
According to work culture experts, it is important to have data on employee satisfaction.
But the data itself is useless unless the company takes the necessary steps.
The fact is that once a company asks for feedback from its employees, major changes can occur.
And if change doesn’t happen quickly – in the worst case, at all – it can lead to disappointment and disinterest on the part of employees.
“Once you’ve asked for 4,000 opinions, you need to be prepared for 4,000 conversations,” said Russell Raath, director of consulting at Kotter International, which has seen many companies rely too heavily on the data itself.
