Creating a graphic novel: the story of A Castle in England
The small Scottish Castle recently played a leading role in the Squeeze music video, and Margaret Thatcher also found refuge in it during the 1970s and 1980s.
But from his cozy spot by the Bewl River in Kent, UK, Scottney has witnessed 700 years of turbulent history that inspired the curly Jamie Rhodes of York County – known for his fondness for historical documents – to create a graphic novel.
“Looking at the handwriting of a man who is 300 years after his death fascinates me,” Rhodes says with a serious face.
"When I hold a letter in my hands, I feel a personal connection."
The graphic novel A Castle in England documents the lives of families who lived at Scottney Castle from the Middle Ages to the Edwardian period. Each story is illustrated by a different British artist - Isaac Lenkiewicz, Briony May Smith, William Exley, Becky Palmer and Isabel Greenberg.
However, this is not Rhodes’ first book inspired by archives: he is also the author of Dead Men’s Teeth and Other Stories (2014), a collection of British Library-inspired documents – a project that was very emotional for him.
"I was intrigued by the thumbprint on a letter written by a double agent in the 1970s who worked for the Jacobites," he said.
"That's his thumbprint!
And letters always smell like smoke, because in those days you had to light a candle to read.
When I smell the letter now, 300 years later, it's like I'm going back in time.
I love the archives!
For someone who is so fascinated by old papers, the support of the National Trust and Arts Council England and the opportunity to spend almost four months in the castle is almost like a dream.
Rhodes spent time exploring the Victorian "new" castle, traversing archives, and studying many treasures and curiosities, such as the head of a hyena on a wall and bottles that had been thrown into a ditch for centuries.
He walked around the property, examining the ruins of the old castle, talking to the janitors, gardeners, and occasionally also the artists who worked on the illustrations for his book.
At night, he drank whiskey and wrote.
The confidential history of Scottney is relatively unknown, as the National Trust gained access to the documents only in 2006 after the death of the last heir, Elizabeth Hussey.
When Rhodes arrived ten years later, the staff was only beginning to penetrate the archives, which Rhodes described in words such as “for centuries aristocrats have thrown their hands around saying, ‘Take this to the attic.’”
Diaries, letters from the British Empire, maps showing possessions: "You may think that the land dispute is boring," Rhodes said, "but I came across one case where two families were fighting over birch.
Stop it, people!"
Some of the stories in the book use the castle as a springboard and delve deeper into English history, including a story called The Labourer, which follows a man who leaves the newly built castle to join the English Rebellion of 1381.
“I found a record of a revolt at the castle in 1380, which was called the Knightly Families of Kent and Sussex in the book,” Rhodes said.
“The English Rebellion actually started in this area and I thought the Rebellion was a good starting point.
Maybe they have something to do with each other after all.”
Other stories are firmly tied to the history of the castle - for example, The Priest, which tells the story of a Jesuit priest, whom Darrell's family hid for seven years during the English Reformation.
Or The Smuggler about an 18th-century smuggler named Arthur Darrell, who allegedly staged his own funeral when he filled a coffin with stones (which was only discovered a few years after the coffin was discovered).
Rhodes' favorite family is the Darrells: "I was intrigued by the male generation - the men of that time were always in debt and spending money on things they couldn't afford.
Different generations of the Darrell family have dealt with it by marrying rich or old housewives – I imagine they were handsome gentlemen who liked to shake their heads at their heirs.”
With the end of his stay at the castle, Rhodes searches for other adventures.
He recently returned from a two-week retreat in the Finnish wilderness, where he drew inspiration for his next book about El<0xC3><0xA4>m<0xC3><0xA4>nm<0xC3><0xA4>ki, a former sanatorium from the early 20th century that was consumed by nature.
