Red meat, dairy products, and chocolate may ease symptoms of inflammatory bowel disease (IBD)
For your digestive system, red meat and dairy products can be a nightmare.
But a new study suggests the opposite: a diet rich in animal protein and dairy products could help relieve the symptoms of inflammatory bowel disease.
The incurable disease, which affects up to 1.3 million people in the US and 300,000 patients in the UK, causes abdominal pain and bloody diarrhea, weight loss and extreme fatigue.
Patients are usually reminded not to use meat and dairy products to relieve symptoms. However, researchers at the University of Washington have found that the essential amino acid tryptophan contained in the protein helps to create immune cells that support intestinal resistance.
The study’s lead author, Dr. Marco Colonna, explained that immune cells protect the gut and ensure the destruction of harmful microbes from food.
The number of inflammatory cells is balanced by the number of cells that support tolerance and protect the body without damaging sensitive tissue.
As soon as the bowls of the scale lean to the side of the inflammation, inflammatory bowel disease can occur.
As part of the research, the researchers found the presence of immune cells supporting body tolerance in the stomach of mice with a specific bacterium.
This bacterium requires the presence of tryptophan - one of the building blocks of proteins - to form cells.
Professor Colonna said: “We found a link between one species of bacteria – Lactobacillus reuteri – which is a common part of the gut microbiome and the development of cells that support body tolerance.
The more tryptophan mice had in their diet, the more immune cells they had.”
He also suggested that if the same holds true for humans, then a combination of L. reuteri and tryptophan-rich diets would help develop a more tolerant and less inflammatory gut environment.
A post-graduate researcher, Dr. Luisa Cervantes-Barraganwas, in a study of a type of immune cell that promotes body tolerance, found that one group of test mice had these cells, while the other group of the same mice bred separately lacked the cells.
She deduced that one group of mice had a different gut microbiome — a community of bacteria, viruses, and fungi that normally inhabit the gastrointestinal tract.
The guts of the mice were tested by DNA sequencing, and the researchers found six types of bacteria in mice with immune cells that the second group of mice lacked.
Mice that were kept in a sterile environment and lacked a gut microbiome — so they did not develop this kind of immune cells — were given L. reuteri bacteria — and formed immune cells.
To understand how the bacterium affects the immune system, the researchers cultured L. reuteri in a liquid and then transferred small amounts of the fluid — without the bacterium — to undeveloped immune cells that were kept in isolation.
Immune cells have evolved into tolerant cells.
After removing the active ingredient from the liquid, it turned out to be a byproduct of tryptophan metabolism known as indolyl-3-acetic acid.
When researchers doubled the amount of tryptophan in the diet of mice, the amount of these cells increased by 50 percent. After halving the doses of tryptophan, at the same time, the number of cells decreased by half.
Dr. Cervantes-Barragan explained that humans have the same tolerant cells as mice, and most of us keep L. reuteri bacteria in our gastrointestinal tract.
It is not known whether tryptophan byproducts from L. reuteri cause cell development in humans in the same way as in mice, but defects in tryptophan-related genes have been found in people with inflammatory bowel disease.
Dr Cervantes-Barragan added: “Each of us should probably strive for the development of these cells, because they control inflammation of the inner surface of the intestines.
Potentially high levels of tryptophan in the presence of L. reuteri can increase cell populations."
