White House props cost taxpayers thousands of dollars
The White House’s decision to fly a Navy helicopter to South Lawn to celebrate the U.S. manufacturing industry, which took place last month, came at $24,000, according to Navy records published by TIME.
The green-white Sikorsky VH-3D helicopter, also called Marine One in the presence of the president on board, was the highlight of the July 17 program at the White House, which was a showcase of American design programs.
President Donald Trump, Vice President Mike Pence, and several senior White House officials watched a parade of products from all 50 states.
The Connecticut helicopter was displayed next to a Maine yacht, a Wisconsin fire truck, and a Mississippi forklift truck.
A White House military officer issued a fragmentary order, or FRAGO, requesting the presence of a helicopter less than 36 hours before the helicopter landed on South Lawn as part of an "extraordinary" event, Marine Helicopter Squadron One (HMX-1) records show.
“I wanted to make sure you were aware of such an important event,” the HMX-1 commander wrote in an email to his superior, the Navy’s deputy commander for aviation, the day before the event began.
The report indicated that the helicopter would arrive at South Lawn on July 17 at approximately 7:00 p.m. on the occasion of the show, which is scheduled to begin at 3:00 p.m. and will remain in place until the entire site is cleared, which was scheduled to be between 6:00 p.m. and 9:00 p.m.
The e-mail further stated that if there is a delay during the departure from the White House, a replacement crew will be sent for the return flight due to the working hours regulations.
The original crew remained in place that evening, along with the helicopter and a unit of security personnel.
From the records - obtained by TIME - it was not clear whether a second crew was eventually dispatched.
The Hatch Act prevents government officials from using government property for political purposes.
The records indicate that HMX-1 is investigating a possible infringement of this Regulation.
"We were wondering if this was a violation of the Hatch Act and were assured that everything was in order," the commander wrote.
"Sounds like you've been blocked," the deputy commander wrote.
This "Made in America" show was designated by the White House as an official event, and the Hatch Act would not apply to it.
But even official events have political overtones.
While attending the event, the president pushed through Senate-sponsored health reform and talked about trying to rein in government regulation.
The use of air vehicles such as Marine One or Air Force One for political purposes is hardly a new phenomenon.
Presidents use them when they travel.
However, their presence purely for presentation reasons is unusual.
Trump ordered the check in February after the presidential plane rolled in the background during his first rally as part of a campaign in Melbourne, Florida. His Twitter account is swamped with complaints about the use of the presidential plane by his predecessor.
“The White House is pleased to announce the ‘Made in America’ show, which showcases products from all 50 states manufactured by Americans from American materials,” said Lindsay Walters, a spokeswoman for the White House press secretary.
HMX-1 helicopter crews often train landings in the Washington area and at South Lawn and rehearse possible arrivals with the President of the United States to the White House with maximum accuracy.
While Trump attended the G-20 summit in Germany in early July, HMX-1 conducted 58 training landings at the White House.
The flight to the Made in America show was part of the crew’s current training, a state official said.
The helicopter unit flew for another 11 hours on the same day as part of a “non-presidential support mission.”
The White House said no additional props were being paid from taxpayers' money.
A Sikorsky spokesman said the company was not in any way interested in negotiations to expose the helicopter to South Lawn.
HMX-1 does not keep budget records for presidential flights, and the exact cost of the show is difficult to determine, according to the Navy.
According to the Ministry of Defense, the hourly price for the fiscal year 2017, reimbursement of DoD expenses for VH-3D is $24,380 per flight hour.
The unit's logs show a time of 30 minutes from Marine Corps Air Facility Quantico in Virginia and back.
The White House argues that the actual operating cost of the helicopter is well below that amount.
“It’s very misleading to put the cost of taxpayers on the basis of estimates for reimbursements,” Walters said.
“These estimates include personnel, maintenance, and many other hidden costs that are included in annual costs.”
According to a 2015 RAND study, reimbursements for DoD expenses do not include staff costs, but include fuel price, maintenance and contract costs.
The White House press secretary at the time, Sean Spicer, defended the use of the helicopter for parade purposes.
“The idea of this week’s show is to showcase products made in the U.S.,” Spicer said.
“I am aware that Sikorsky and the state of Connecticut are very proud of the fact that they are contributing to the defense of our state, and that they are providing jobs to hundreds, if not thousands, of people.
I think, like most Americans, that we are proud of the helicopter and other military equipment that countless American citizens are involved in making.
This is a fact worth remembering.”
It is not clear whether Trump, during his tour of South Lawn, also looked at the helicopter. With certainty, one can only say that he sat behind the wheel of one of the fire trucks.
Back at the White House, Trump addressed a representative of Sikorsky and joked with the media about his own product fleet.
"I know Sikorsky very well," said the President, "I own three now."
